---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How much does tree removal cost in Pakenham and Cardinia Shire?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Tree removal in Cardinia Shire ranges from around $800 for a small backyard wattle up to $15,000 for a mature 25m+ blue gum next to a house. Most domestic removals sit between $1,500 and $4,500. The price drivers are height, trunk diameter, proximity to buildings and powerlines, whether we can drop it whole or have to climb and section it down, and access for the chipper. Lopping or formative pruning is usually $300–$1,500. Stump grinding is $150–$500 depending on diameter and root spread. Storm callouts are $400–$1,800. Land clearing for a build site runs $2,000–$8,000 per acre. Every quote is fixed-price, written, and free." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do I need a permit to remove a tree in Cardinia Shire?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "It depends on three things: the tree, the zone, and the overlay. Cardinia Shire has a Significant Tree Register, and any tree on it needs a planning permit before pruning or removal — fines for unauthorised removal start at $9,000+. Properties inside a Vegetation Protection Overlay (VPO) or Environmental Significance Overlay (ESO) need a permit for native trees over 10m or with trunk diameter >40cm at 1m height. Dead, dangerous and pest-host trees can usually be removed without a permit under the standard exemptions (10/30 rule near dwellings, hazardous-tree assessment). We check the council mapping for every job at the quote stage and lodge any required permit on your behalf." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is AS 4373 pruning and why does it matter?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "AS 4373-2007 is the Australian Standard for pruning of amenity trees — it's what a Cert IV arborist follows when removing a branch correctly. Cuts are made just outside the branch collar (not flush with the trunk, not leaving a stub) so the tree can compartmentalise the wound and seal it. No more than 25% of the live canopy is removed in a single growth season. Branches over 50mm are three-cut undercut to prevent bark tearing. The opposite of AS 4373 is 'topping' or 'lopping' — flat-cutting the head off a tree — which gardeners with chainsaws still do, and which destroys the tree's structural integrity, kills it slowly, and creates dangerous epicormic regrowth that drops limbs in storms 5–10 years later. We never top healthy trees." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do you do 24/7 emergency storm response in Cardinia Shire?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Yes — we run a 24-hour storm response service across all of Cardinia Shire. Standard call-out window for a tree on a house, car or driveway is 60–120 minutes for Pakenham, Officer and Beaconsfield; 90–180 minutes for the eastern shire (Bunyip, Garfield, Tonimbuk). After major storm events (the spring/summer north-westerlies that bring down half-rotten limbs across the shire), we triage by danger level — anything on a house or blocking access first, hung-up 'widow-makers' second, garden cleanup last. Insurance documentation provided for every emergency callout. Phone (03) 9003 0108 — out of hours rings the duty arborist." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Why shouldn't I just let a gardener 'lop' my tree?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Because gardeners who 'lop' trees — flat-cut the top off — aren't pruning, they're disfiguring. A topped gum or oak grows back as a thicket of weakly-attached epicormic shoots from the cut, all attached to the trunk by paper-thin bark unions. Within 5–10 years those shoots are 4–8m long and drop unpredictably in storms. The tree also routes most of its photosynthesis into new shoots instead of root-defence, so decay enters at the cut and the trunk hollows over the next decade. We see the consequences every week on storm callouts: trees that were 'lopped' to be safer are exactly the ones that fall. A Cert IV arborist will either prune properly to AS 4373 or recommend removal if the tree's structure is already compromised. Lopping is the worst of both worlds." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do you grind stumps below grade so I can replant or pave over them?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Yes. Standard stump grind is 100–150mm below grade, which is enough for re-turfing, garden beds and most landscaping. For pavers, concrete slabs, footings or pool work we grind 300mm+ below, and we follow the major lateral roots out 1–2m and grind those too — otherwise the root mass rots over 5–10 years and creates voids that crack pavers. We bring two grinders: a 30cm narrow-access grinder that fits through a 900mm gate, and a 76cm tow-behind for big paddock stumps. Cleanup includes removing the grindings or backfilling with topsoil at your choice." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Are you insured? Are your climbers qualified?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Yes to both. We carry $20 million public liability and full WorkCover. Our climbers hold Cert IV in Arboriculture (minimum), Working at Heights, EWP licences and chainsaw cross-cut and tree-felling tickets. Every job has a documented Job Safety Analysis and exclusion zone before the first cut. Insurance certificates and qualifications are provided on request — and you should ask any tree contractor for them before they bring a chainsaw onto your block. The cheap cash-job operators on Facebook Marketplace usually have neither, and if one of them puts a tree through your neighbour's roof, it's your problem." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How quickly can you get to a fallen tree?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "For a genuine emergency (tree on house, tree blocking driveway, tree on car, hung-up limb over a footpath) we aim for 60–120 minutes anywhere in central Cardinia Shire — Pakenham, Officer, Beaconsfield, Cardinia Lakes, Heritage Springs, Berwick edge. The eastern shire (Bunyip, Garfield, Nar Nar Goon, Tynong, Tonimbuk) is 90–180 minutes. After a major weather event (the type that drops 50+ trees across the shire in a night) we triage by danger level and may run a 24–48 hour queue for non-emergency garden cleanup. Phone (03) 9003 0108 — calls go to the duty arborist after hours, not a call centre." }
    }
  ]
};
---
<Layout
  title="Cardinia Tree Services | Tree Removal, Lopping & Stump Grinding | (03) 9003 0108"
  description="Tree removal, lopping, stump grinding and 24/7 storm response across Pakenham, Officer, Beaconsfield, Cardinia Lakes & all of Cardinia Shire. Cert IV arborists. AS 4373 pruning. $20M insured. Free fixed-price quote.">
  <Fragment slot="head">
    <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(faqSchema)} />
  </Fragment>

<style>
  /* Image-banner integration (added 2026-06-04) */
  .hero {
